rical values often struggle to grasp the concept of representing unknown quantities with letters, such as 'x' or 'y'. This abstraction can lead to confusion when manipulating equations and solving for these variables. A pedagogical approach that emphasizes concrete examples and visual representations can bridge this gap. For instance, illustrating the concept of a variable using real-world scenarios, such as representing the unknown cost of a mango with simple linear equations like 'two 'x', plus three equals seven' and progressing to more complex equations involving fractions or exponents, can make the concept more tangible. Furthermore, utilizing manipulative aids like algebra tiles can provide a visual and tactile understanding of algebraic expressions and equations.\"\n}"
